App Store Anger
---------------

The root of tech=E2=80=99s frustration with Apple =E2=80=94 including long-=
time Apple developers, traditionally the company=E2=80=99s most ardent supp=
orters =E2=80=94 is the App Store. The App Store is the ultimate example of=
 Apple leveraging consumers=E2=80=99 desire for their products to gain powe=
r over an ecosystem; in this case, though, the ecosystem isn=E2=80=99t musi=
c labels or cellular providers, but rather app developers, which is to say =
everyone else in tech. Smartphones are essential devices, and Apple makes t=
he best smartphone, which means their power over developers is absolute.

Apple is not afraid to exercise this power, and it=E2=80=99s important to n=
ote that in the early days of the iPhone the company=E2=80=99s control work=
ed in developers=E2=80=99 favor. Apple decreed that 3rd-party apps could on=
ly be installed via the App Store, which would review every app; free apps =
wouldn=E2=80=99t have to pay anything, while Apple would take 30% of paid a=
pps. This led to an absolute explosion in the market: consumers, who had be=
en scarred by the 2000=E2=80=99s era of malware and viruses, shook off thei=
r reticence to install software and embraced the App Store, leading to an e=
xplosion of app-based businesses. An important development was the 2009 add=
ition of in-app purchase, which unlocked entirely new business models for g=
ames in particular. Subscriptions for publications came in 2011, although i=
t took another five years for the business model to be available to all app=
lications.

