If you were to boil Apple=E2=80=99s philosophy and attractiveness to custom=
ers to one word, that word would be =E2=80=9Cintegration.=E2=80=9D And gues=
s what? First party integration is bad for third-party developers =E2=80=94=
 everything is a tradeoff. This is where the nuance I discussed in App Stor=
e Arguments becomes much more black-and-white. Yes, Apple created the iPhon=
e and the App Store and, under current U.S. antitrust doctrine, almost cert=
ainly has the right to impose whatever taxes it wishes on third parties, in=
cluding 30% on purchases and the first year of subscriptions, and completel=
y cutting off developers from their customers. Antitrust law, though, while=
 governed by Supreme Court precedent, is not a matter of constitutionality:=
 it stems from laws passed by Congress, and it can be changed by new laws p=
assed by Congress.

One of the central planks of many of those pushing for new laws in this are=
a are significant limitations on the ability of platforms to offer apps and=
 services, or integrate them in any way that advantages their offerings. In=
 this potential world it=E2=80=99s not simply problematic that Apple charge=
s Spotify 30%, or else forces the music streaming service to hope that user=
s figure out how to subscribe on the web, even as Apple Music has a fully i=
ntegrated sign-up flow and no 30% tax; it is also illegal to incorporate Ap=
ple Music into SharePlay or Shared-with-you or Photos, or in the most extre=
me versions of these proposed laws, even have Apple Music at all. This limi=
tation would apply to basically every WWDC announcement: say good-bye to Qu=
ick Note or SharePlay-as-an-exclusive-service, or any number of Apple=E2=80=
=99s integrated offerings.

I think these sorts of limitations would be disappointing as a user =E2=80=
=94 integration really does often lead to better outcomes sooner =E2=80=94 =
and would be a disaster for Apple. The entire company=E2=80=99s differentia=
tion is predicated on integration, including its ability to abuse its App S=
tore position, and it would be a huge misstep if the inability to resist th=
e latter imperiled the former.

Last week this danger manifested, not as new legislation, but as this lawsu=
it, which attacks Apple=E2=80=99s integration much more than it attacks the=
 App Store. I think, though, that it was Apple=E2=80=99s policies around th=
e App Store that created the conditions for this lawsuit in the first place=
.

In short, I suspect the DOJ doesn=E2=80=99t want to follow in Epic=E2=80=99=
s footsteps, but they do want to sue Apple, so they framed Apple=E2=80=99s =
defining characteristic =E2=80=94 integration =E2=80=94 in the most unchari=
table light possible to make their case. To put it another way, the Epic ca=
se may have shown that Apple=E2=80=99s policies around the App Store were (=
mostly) legal, but that didn=E2=80=99t mean they were right; now the DOJ, l=
ooking for another point of vulnerability, is trying to make the case that =
Apple=E2=80=99s right approach in delivering an integrated experience is in=
 fact illegal.

During the Epic trial John Gruber wished that Apple would relax its approac=
h to the App Store ( https://daringfireball.net/2021/06/app_store_the_schil=
ler_cut ) :

What=E2=80=99s weirdest about Apple=E2=80=99s antitrust and PR problems rel=
ated to the App Store is that the App Store is a side hustle for Apple. Yes=
 it=E2=80=99s earning Apple $10+ billion a year, and even for Apple that=E2=
=80=99s significant. But it=E2=80=99s not Apple=E2=80=99s main business by =
a long shot. To my knowledge no company in history has ever gotten into ant=
itrust hot water over a side business so comparatively small to its overall=
 business. Apple doesn=E2=80=99t need this.

I think Apple=E2=80=99s senior leadership=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89Cook in=
 particular=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89truly does believe that Apple has ear=
ned every dollar it generates from third-party software in the App Store, a=
nd that their policies in place are just and fair. That righteousness came =
out on the stand in the Epic trial. But even if Apple=E2=80=99s executives =
are correct=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89if the current rules and revenue spli=
ts could somehow be proven to be dialed in to a hypothetical Platonic ideal=
 of fairness to all parties involved=E2=80=89=E2=80=94=E2=80=89that doesn=
=E2=80=99t change the fact that so many developers see it otherwise.

I don=E2=80=99t think the developers are wrong, but even if they are wrong,=
 it=E2=80=99s not good for Apple that they=E2=80=99re so unhappy, and feel =
so aggrieved. It=E2=80=99s not good for Apple that developers don=E2=80=99t=
 see the App Store as a platform that works in their interests. Like the Ap=
ple logo, =E2=80=9Cdeveloper goodwill=E2=80=9D has no price tag.

To the extent I am right =E2=80=94 and yes, it is impossible to prove a cou=
nterfactual =E2=80=94=C2=A0the price tag of Apple=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cside h=
ustle=E2=80=9D is even higher than Gruber thought: I believe that if Apple =
had done even the bare minimum with the App Store =E2=80=94 i.e. removing t=
he anti-steering provision and not going after small developers with online=
 services =E2=80=94 it wouldn=E2=80=99t be in a position of having to defen=
d what actually makes Apple Apple. It would, at a minimum, have a lot more =
people on its side.

